headline.main: Paid Notice: Deaths  ARON, ROBERTO

lead_paragraph: ARON--Roberto. Husband, father, step-father, grandfather, great-grandfather, passed away on June 24, 2014 at the age of 98. Born on November 1, 1915, he was raised in Argentina and moved to Chile where he attended University. Upon receiving his LL.B. degree from the University of Chile's Faculty of Law, he embarked on a seven decade career as an international lawyer, diplomat, law professor and the author of law textbooks and other scholarly works. While raising a family in Chile, he made Aliyah to Israel in 1957. After joining that country's bar, he entered a private law practice and endeavored to raise money for Israel's fledgling economy thru the sale of government bonds in Latin America and other Spanish-speaking countries. He made countless speaking tours as Israel's goodwill ambassador and his success was rewarded in 1974 with a position as a legal adviser with Israel's mission to the United Nations under the leadership of Ambassador Chiam Herzog. His love of learning led him to earn three Master of Law degrees at New York University in International Legal Studies in Corporate and Commercial Law and in Jewish Talmudic Law. For 14 years, Mr. Aron served as the chair of Trial Advocacy at the Law School of Tel Aviv University. He also was a guest teacher at New York University's School of Law. A professor of economics at St. John's University in Jamaica, New York for the better part of three decades, Ms. Shah's passion for Keynesian and feminist economics was matched only by her sense of social justice and her fondness for all animals, which she expressed in poems. Of course, her love for her family, and particularly her grandchildren, topped everything else. Ms. Shah was born in Satara, India in 1937, and came to the United States as president's fellow to pursue a Ph.D. in economics at Columbia University, where she received her second master's degree in 1964. She later completed doctoral courses at the New School for Social Research. In 1961, Ms. Shah also met her future husband, Shashi K. Shah; they celebrated their fiftieth anniversary in 2013. Ms. Shah loved teaching young minds about the workings of the modern economy and the history of economic thought. More often than not, her students would often tell her how accessible she made a subject they initially approached with dread. Ms. Shah also had a passion for the natural world, which she expressed in poems she wrote about robins nesting in the bushes outside her New Canaan home or the remarkable devotion of dogs. Her love of music ranged from Bach to bluegrass. But her greatest love was for her grandchildren who kept her smiles always in bloom. Ms. Shah was an ethically principled person who worked well with others and greatly appreciated their presence in her life. Her family members feel fortunate to have had her among them happy, peppy and bursting with love, kindness and compassion. They shall miss her and remember her forever. Among the bereaved whom Ms. Shah leaves behind are her husband, Shashi K. Shah of New Canaan, son and daughter-in-law, Sanjit and Mary Shah of South Salem, New York, two grandchildren, Mina and Vikram Shah, her brother Sharad and his wife Sandhya Janorkar of Mumbai, India, and her nieces Anju Suvernpatki of Guelph, Ontario, Sonal Sathe of North Bergen, New Jersey, Lata Manerikar, Nandini Alawani of Mumbai, India, and their respective families. Ms. Shah also leaves behind dozens of young people who came from abroad to study in the United States to whom she served as a surrogate mother, and with whom she maintained warm relations long after they became adults. lead_paragraph: ARON--Roberto. Husband, father, step-father, grandfather, great-grandfather, passed away on June 24, 2014 at the age of 98. Born on November 1, 1915, he was raised in Argentina and moved to Chile where he attended University. Upon receiving his LL.B. degree from the University of Chile's Faculty of Law, he embarked on a seven decade career as an international lawyer, diplomat, law professor and the author of law textbooks and other scholarly works. While raising a family in Chile, he made Aliyah to Israel in 1957. After joining that country's bar, he entered a private law practice and endeavored to raise money for Israel's fledgling economy thru the sale of government bonds in Latin America and other Spanish-speaking countries. He made countless speaking tours as Israel's goodwill ambassador and his success was rewarded in 1974 with a position as a legal adviser with Israel's mission to the United Nations under the leadership of Ambassador Chiam Herzog. His love of learning led him to earn three Master of Law degrees at New York University in International Legal Studies in Corporate and Commercial Law and in Jewish Talmudic Law. For 14 years, Mr. Aron served as the chair of Trial Advocacy at the Law School of Tel Aviv University. He also was a guest teacher at New York University's School of Law.
